==Onmyoji==
With the advent of the noble ghost faith, the onmyōdō became even more diverse. For example, spells such as {{ill|Katatagae|lt=changing the direction for good fortune|ja|方違え}} and {{ill|Monoimi|lt=self-consecration|ja|物忌み}}, rituals such as the Festival of the [[Dongyue Dadi|Great Emperor of the Sacred Mountain of the East]], and [[Yu the Great|Uho]] steps (hempai<ref name="kosaka">{{cite magazine |last=Kosaka |first=Shinji |date=6 October 2001 |title=陰陽師が反閇をつとめるとはどういうことか |trans-title=What does it mean for an onmyōji to do hempai? |url=https://ddnavi.com/davinci/backnumber/90/ |language=ja |magazine=da Vinci |volume=October, 2001 |location=[[Chiyoda, Tokyo|Chiyoda City]], Tokyo Metropolis, Japan |publisher=[[Kadokawa Future Publishing]]}}</ref>), which were often seen in onmyōdō practices, originated from Taoism, and rice scattering and [[Norito|liturgical incantations]] {{Citation needed span|originated from ancient Shinto.|date=September 2011}} 
