== Monoimi in Folk Practices ==
Similar customs have been observed in folk practices. Festival participants were traditionally required to refrain from singing, consuming meat, or handling {{ill|night soil|ja|下肥|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/night soil|qq=}} during the festival period. Certain regions also prohibited the consumption of specific foods, such as cucumbers or sesame.

Seasonal monoimi was also practiced to prepare for the arrival of deities. For example, on {{ill|Kōzushima|ja|神津島|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kōzushima|qq=}}, residents abstain from entering the mountains, cease work, avoid noise, and extinguish lights on the night of January 24th (lunar calendar) to welcome a sea deity.<ref>{{cite|和書|author={{ill|Tanaka Norikazu|ja|田中宣一|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tanaka Norikazu|qq=}}|contribution=忌み日|editor={{ill|Sakurai Tokutarō|ja|桜井徳太郎|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sakurai Tokutarō|qq=}}|title=民間信仰辞典|publisher=東京堂出版|year=1980|page=31}}</ref>

Key festival figures, such as {{ill|Tōya|ja|頭屋|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tōya|qq=}}, were often subject to extended periods of monoimi. These included designated periods for sansai and chisai, with the strictest periods requiring them to reside in separate firehouses (separate hearths) to avoid defilement.

